# RESPONSIBILITY-MAP.md — Human–Agent Decision/Approval Grid

Per-feature grid naming which decisions the agent makes autonomously, which require human approval, and what authority each level has. ADLC P1 deliverable; the source article calls this out as "no equivalent in SDLC."

Filled via `/responsibility-map` skill. Updated as new decision points are discovered in P4/P7.

---

## Feature: [name] (H-NNN)

### Decision points

> **Multi-agent grids (F5.3 · Trial 3)**: when ≥2 agents share a decision chain, add a **Chain** column with sequence numbers (`1 → 2 → 3 …`) and use the `Who` column to name the *specific agent* (`classifier-agent`, `billing-specialist`, `coordinator-agent`) instead of generic `agent`. Each row in a chain inherits the downstream authority of the prior row — make this explicit. Single-agent features omit the Chain column.

| Chain | Decision | Who | Approval | Authority | Escalation trigger |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | [Low-stakes routing decision, e.g. "classify ticket domain"] | `classifier-agent` | `none` | scoped (enum-bounded) | confidence < 0.7 → human-triage |
| 2 | [Specialist draft, e.g. "draft billing response"] | `billing-specialist` | `none` (intermediate) | scoped (own-domain only) | cross-domain detected → coordinator |
| 3 | [Quality gate, e.g. "review draft + decide send/escalate"] | `coordinator-agent` | `human-pre` (pilot) → `human-post` (post-pilot) | advisory | confidence < 0.8 OR refund-keyword → human |
| — | [Irreversible action, e.g. "issue refund"] | `human` | always human-only | n/a (advisory only) | refund-keyword detected → flag human |

> Add 1 row per concrete decision point. Real features typically have 5-10 rows. Categories: action authority · quality gates · cost ceilings · unsafe-zone detection · conflict resolution. For peer-network / hierarchical multi-agent patterns, use `1a · 1b · 1c` (peer) or `1.1 · 1.2` (hierarchical) chain notation.

### Unsafe-autonomy zones

Categories where the agent MUST defer to a human regardless of confidence:

- **[Irreversible action category]**: [rule — when to hard-handoff]
- **[Legal / compliance category]**: [rule]
- **[Financial transaction category]**: [rule]
- **[PII / sensitive-data category]**: [rule]

### Compliance check

Mapping HG-declared constraints (from HYPOTHESIS.md kill-criteria) to grid rows that enforce them:

- Constraint: [from H-NNN] → enforced by: [row reference above]
- Constraint: [from H-NNN] → enforced by: [row reference]

### Cross-agent context-handoff policy (multi-agent only · F5.7 Trial 3)

> Required when the grid has ≥2 distinct `Who` agents. Omit for single-agent features.

How context passes between agents — declared once, audited at every handoff. Trial 3 found inter-agent prompt-injection succeeds when handoff envelopes pass raw user content; explicit policy is the v2.4 mitigation pattern.

- **Handoff envelope format**: structured JSON only (instruction-following patterns in user input cannot survive JSON-encoding). Free-text passthrough is **forbidden** between agents.
- **What CAN pass**: classifier output (enum), specialist draft (string field), confidence score (float), provenance pointer (record ID).
- **What CANNOT pass**: raw user input verbatim (must be re-quoted under a typed field); upstream agent's "system" or "instruction" framing; tool-call traces from prior agent.
- **Pre-filter at boundary**: regex strip on common injection patterns (`ignore previous`, `you are now`, `system:`, code-fence with directive language) BEFORE passing to next agent.
- **Role-stability prompt**: each downstream agent re-asserts its role in its own system prompt — never relies on upstream framing.
- **Audit hook**: log every handoff envelope to the eval suite's per-agent stream; injection-resistance metric runs over these logs.

### Kill-switch

How a human stops a runaway agent on this feature:
- **Per-task**: [mechanism, e.g. flag on individual record disables agent for that record]
- **Per-user / per-cohort**: [allowlist / opt-out mechanism]
- **Per-agent (multi-agent only · F5.9 v2.5)**: operator can disable any single agent within <30s; disabled traffic falls back to either (a) the human queue OR (b) a designated peer/upstream agent. List per-agent overrides explicitly so on-call doesn't have to choose under pressure. Single-agent features omit this row.
- **Global**: [feature flag · canary-shrink · routing override; specify recovery time]

### Open questions (defer to AG)

Decisions that emerge during scoping but resolve cleanly at architecture phase:
- [question 1] → resolves at AG (e.g. "does agent have read access to customer history?")
- [question 2] → resolves at AG

